<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Name:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAqIAAAACCAYAAACDgr40AAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABASURBVFhH7dZBDQBACAQxZGEJ/wLuAiLg000w0MyDiF7lcww0oAENaEADGtCABtYamCfUCBAgQIAAAQIECBwIfPJqRD14FzhkAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC" width="674" height="2" alt="" style="margin-left:0pt; margin-top:4pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65536" /></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the National Farmers Union</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU represents more than 55,000 farming members in England and Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and we have some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 41,000 countryside members with an interest in farming and the country. The NFU welcomes the opportunity to make a submission to the Environment Audit Committee on Biodiversity Offsetting. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodiversity offsetting appears to be an attractive concept and could offer opportunities, and a financial benefit,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to some farmers and landowners. For biodiversity offsetting to become a realistic proposition offset providers (i.e. the land manager providing the biodiversity offset) will need to come forward from the agricultural sector.  Without offset providers the market for biodiversity offsets will not function. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Learning from the Government’s biodiversity offset pilots we have established that potential biodiversity offset providers need many reassurances before considering entering in to an agreement.  The areas we have identified, and have not been fully addressed in the Government’s green paper consultation, are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alignment with Common Agricultural Policy regimes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Relationship with Payments for Ecosystem services</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Length of agreement</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fair financial return</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Financial security</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Covering full costs of offsetting</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What is the offset provider being asked to deliver?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Contractual arrangements for the offset provider</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Flexibility post biodiversity offsetting agreement</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Land tenure</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Being an offset provider is voluntary</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We give further thought to each of these points in our submission below. We have focused our comments on enabling offset provision, rather than covering all aspects contained in the Government’s green paper. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Alignment with Common Agricultural Policy regimes</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Farmers will need to consider how the offset sits alongside their business interests.  For example, much more clarity is needed as to how a biodiversity offset interacts with Common Agricultural Policy schemes.  Having a biodiversity offset should not lead to the loss of CAP payments, for example, by not meeting cross compliance requirements on the offset land, which could trigger the loss of all CAP payments. There needs to be more certainty about how land used for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-environment schemes or to meet new ‘greening’ requirements can be used for an offset without incurring CAP penalties. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given the proposed length of offset provision there needs to be flexibility to respond to changes to CAP implementation policy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">None of these issues are considered within the green paper.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Relationship with Payments for Ecosystem services</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The green paper does not address how biodiversity offsetting sits with wider Government policy areas, such payments for ecosystem services.  Would it be possible to receive Payment of Ecosystem Services (PES) payments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, e.g. water quality improvements associated with catchment land management,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as have a biodiversity offset?  For example, there are new initiatives coming forward for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carbon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> offsetting, so again there needs to be consideration how these sit alongside each other.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Length of agreement</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We do not believe that agreements should automatically exist in perpetuity and bind successors in title, as proposed in the Law Commission’s recent consultation paper; but they should offer flexibility as to the conservation requirements and the length of the obligations. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU is unsure about the extent to which offsetting might be taken up by its membership.  If biodiversity offsetting will be required that exist in perpetuity, we can see that this type of long term agreement could be off-putting to a number of our members – to bind their land into a particular type of management or land use for long periods of time, over what may be many generations of farming families, may not suit their circumstances.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fair financial return</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The financial provision for biodiversity offsets must provide a reasonable return that is attractive for the off-setting provider / farmer to engage.  The annual costs will need to be agreed between the offset provider (farmer) and the developer or his representative.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The offset provider will take in to account the length of agreement and costs:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offset providers will expect the financial provision to cover the full length of the agreement, whether that agreement is provided by a covenant and/or management plan. If the expectation is for the offset to be provided in perpetuity then this must be factored in to the costs provided to the provider.  However, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can see that this type of long term agreement could be off-putting to a number of our members – to bind their land into a particular type of management or land use for long periods of time may not suit their circumstances.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It would be unreasonable to expect the offset provider to be satisfied with an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">income forgone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> approach to value offset provision. Our interest in offsetting that it is a market-based approach to addressing biodiversity loss and one which should better value biodiversity loss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Financial security</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the offset provider is to be paid for on an annual basis for their contracted activity it is important that the funds are available for the duration of the offset.  We do have concerns about whether those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">buying offsets (developer or intermediary) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will have the necessary financial tools in place to accommodate the requirement for providing habitat in perpetuity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or contracted timescale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. There needs to be security for the offset provider for funds to be made available for the whole life of the agreement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">/ offset</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, covering all eventualities.  So if the fund holder goes bankrupt the funds remain available or the offset provider can exit the agreement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Covering full costs of offsetting</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">objective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the green paper </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of avoiding additional costs to businesses.  This commitment needs to cover all costs to the business, not just that of acquiring planning permission.  Hence, it must include costs to businesses in terms of the timescales and additional administration associated with planning permission, costs of delivering and maintaining the biodiversity offset over the lifespan of the offset, monitoring and advice provision for the offset provider and any environmental audits required.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government’s green paper does not consider the full cost of biodiversity offsetting. The first examples of biodiversity offsetting in England have not been fully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For example, it has been reported recently that Taylor Wimpey is to buy an offset to create a meadow on a chalk escarpment in Oxfordshire.  The cost is reported to be £51,000 for 2.2ha.  The agreement is only for 15 years, much below the expected length of offsetting provision set out in the green paper.    The land value is in the region of £37,000, leaving £13,000 for habitat creation and management over 15 years.  It is assumed some costs are absorbed by the environmental group contracted to deliver the offset.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals in the green paper are for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an in-perpetuity (not defined but assumed to be more than 99 years) change in land management.  If the biodiversity offsetting is predicated on these initial figures then the actual costs to developers will be misleading.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If developers are to be encouraged to participate, they will need more information on the full costs of offsetting and the legal liabilities that result from entering in to such an agreement.  The green paper does not explain what costs the developer will incur when commissioning an offset.  In part, we assume, this is because the roles of different parties have not been defined. Until these are better defined then the cost of an offset will need to cover all aspects of the offset provision.  One could reasonably expect the developer’s costs for the offset to include: the costs of setting up the legal arrangements; monitoring; providing advice to the offset provider; on-going legal costs; management requirements of the offset; and, any reduction in the value of land used for the offset.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As indicated above the offset provider will want a reasonable return for offset provision.  Our interest in offsetting it that it is a market based approach to address biodiversity loss and one which should value biodiversity gains.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This will go beyond ‘income foregone’ which is used to calculate the payments for relatively short term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-environment schemes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the offset provider being asked to deliver? </span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further, as written, the green paper does not set out what is required from the biodiversity offset provider.  It does not say what the provider is being required to do with his land.  Is the offset payment for managing land in a certain way or for the delivery of an environmental outcome?  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offset providers will need to understand what they are being contracted to provide.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a suggestion that the offset provider would agree a management plan.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ho is the management plan agreed with and how can the plan be varied to account for, say, weather changes or unforeseeable circumstances?  The current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-environment schemes have a clear route for dealing with such issues – but this issue is not discussed at all in the green paper. Biodiversity offset providers will want to know how the offset is monitored and by whom before entering in to an agreement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Contractual arrangements for the offset provider</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The green paper is not clear how the contractual arrangements work for the offset provider.  It does not set out who the offset provider will be contracting with or what the legal consequences of not delivering the offset will be.  Clearly, failure to create the right habitat could be due to incorrect advice, unsuitable location or a change in weather patterns.  Legal recourse will need to recognise these.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-environment schemes have arrangements in place to allow for changes in management of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-environment scheme, say, in response to weather patterns or unforeseeable circumstances. Similar provisions will need to be in place for biodiversity offset provision. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodiversity offset providers will want to know </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who will be providing this advice, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how the offset </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> monitored</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and how disputes are managed.  The offset provider will require this information before entering in to an agreement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Flexibility post biodiversity offsetting agreement</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Land is one of farmers’ main business assets. As such, farmers will want the flexibility to return their land to agricultural production at the end of the offset agreement. However, where the biodiversity offset does not allow for this, e.g. wetland habitat creation, then this needs to be recognised in the price paid for offset provision. And, if the intention is to achieve protected status, e.g. SSSI designation, then this must be clear at the outset of the agreement, so the cost of the offset can be calculated fairly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the offset provider is clear this is the expectation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Land tenure</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Land tenure could also present a problem for those with tenancies interested in offsetting or with a landlord who is considering entering land into an offset agreement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This issue needs to be addressed to find appropriate solutions for both parties. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Being an offset provider is voluntary</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Being an offset provider should be voluntary. There is a danger that the local biodiversity strategies and potential requirements for a specific type of habitat creation will influence land use.  We do have concerns that infrastructure projects will inflict biodiversity provision on land managers, for example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under HS2 where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">landowners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> no choice in regard to the tree planting, balance ponds, created wet areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that are being created. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU therefore believe there is much work to be done to bring forward biodiversity offsets from farmers.  The issues outlined above need to be addressed to ensure offset providers can come forward with a full understanding of the commitment being entered in to. Without this it will constrain the provision of offsets and may constrain the planning process. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">17 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0.5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAq4AAAACCAYAAACZvl66AAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABASURBVFhH7dZRCQBACERBY1nJ/gHu0BQKs2CB4X0Y0at8joEGNKABDWhAAxrQwNoG5mk1AgQIECBAgAABAgcEPsmlV73mTF0VAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC" width="686" height="2" alt="" style="margin-left:0pt; margin-top:-1.8pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65535" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p></div></body></html>